  "text": "Prometheus remote write endpoints enforce TLS and authentication through a multi-layered validation and configuration system:\n\n## Configuration Validation (config/config.go)\n\nThe `RemoteWriteConfig` struct (line 1419) contains embedded `HTTPClientConfig` from prometheus/common package and includes specific auth configs for SigV4, Azure AD, and Google IAM. Its `UnmarshalYAML` method (line 1448) performs critical validation:\n\n1. **TLS Configuration Validation**: Calls `HTTPClientConfig.Validate()` (line 1473) which validates TLS settings including certificate paths, CA files, and insecure skip verify flags through the external prometheus/common package.\n\n2. **Authentication Method Validation**: The `validateAuthConfigs()` function (line 1491) enforces that at most one authentication method can be configured. It checks:\n   - BasicAuth (line 1493)\n   - Authorization/Bearer token (line 1496)\n   - OAuth2 (line 1499)\n   - SigV4 (line 1502)\n   - Azure AD (line 1505)\n   - Google IAM (line 1508)\n   This ensures mutual exclusivity of auth mechanisms.\n\n3. **Header Validation**: The `validateHeaders()` function (line 1529) prevents manual Authorization header manipulation, requiring users to configure auth through proper config parameters instead.\n\n## Client Creation (storage/remote/client.go)\n\nThe `NewWriteClient()` function (line 183) and `NewReadClient()` function (line 151) create HTTP clients for remote write/read endpoints. They process the `ClientConfig` struct (line 128) which includes:\n\n- `HTTPClientConfig` - handled via `config_util.NewClientFromConfig()` (line 152, 188) from prometheus/common, which sets up TLS and standard auth (BasicAuth, BearerToken, OAuth2)\n- `SigV4Config` - wrapped in a SigV4RoundTripper (line 199)\n- `AzureADConfig` - wrapped in an AzureADRoundTripper (line 206)\n- `GoogleIAMConfig` - wrapped in a Google IAM RoundTripper (line 213)\n\n## Storage Integration (storage/remote/write.go)\n\nThe `WriteStorage.ApplyConfig()` method (line 139) applies remote write configuration changes. It extracts authentication configs from `RemoteWriteConfig` and passes them to `NewWriteClient()` (line 169), including HTTPClientConfig, SigV4Config, AzureADConfig, and GoogleIAMConfig.\n\n## Azure AD Bearer Token Handling (storage/remote/azuread/azuread.go)\n\nThe `AzureADConfig.Validate()` method (line 131) validates Azure-specific authentication configurations for Managed Identity, Workload Identity, OAuth, and SDK-based auth. It ensures required fields are present and valid UUIDs/formats.\n\nThe `NewAzureADRoundTripper()` function (line 237) creates an authentication wrapper that intercepts HTTP requests. The `azureADRoundTripper.RoundTrip()` method (line 260) retrieves Azure access tokens and sets the Authorization header with Bearer token format (line 265-266): `Bearer <access_token>`.\n\n## Google IAM Authentication (storage/remote/googleiam/googleiam.go)\n\nThe `NewRoundTripper()` function (line 34) sets up Google Cloud authentication using either provided service account credentials file or default credentials, attaching authentication to requests via the transport layer.\n\n## Compliance Testing (compliance/remote_write_sender_test.go)\n\nThe `TestRemoteWriteSender()` function (line 91) executes comprehensive remote write compliance tests, including configuration parsing and validation through the sender.RunTests() interface, ensuring TLS and authentication enforcement across different protobuf message versions.\n\n## Summary of TLS and Auth Enforcement\n\n1. **TLS Enforcement**: HTTPClientConfig.Validate() validates TLS configuration including certificate verification, CA bundles, and minimum TLS versions through prometheus/common's implementation.\n\n2. **Bearer Token Handling**: Azure AD and Google IAM provide Bearer token authentication through HTTP transport interceptors that automatically add Authorization headers.\n\n3. **Basic Auth Validation**: validateAuthConfigs() enforces that BasicAuth can only be used if no other auth method is configured, ensuring exclusive and explicit authentication configuration.\n\n4. **Mutual Exclusivity**: At most one of six authentication methods (BasicAuth, Authorization/Bearer, OAuth2, SigV4, Azure AD, Google IAM) can be configured per remote write endpoint.\n\n5. **Configuration Validation Chain**: YAML parsing → RemoteWriteConfig.UnmarshalYAML → HTTPClientConfig.Validate() + validateAuthConfigs() + validateHeaders() ensures all TLS and auth settings are validated before the configuration is applied to create actual HTTP clients."
}

